torian England argued about its national identity. Gerard Manley Hopkins, Coventry Patmore, and Robert Bridges used meter to negotiate their relationship to England and the English language; George Saintsbury, Matthew Arnold, and Henry Newbolt worried about the rise of one metrical model among multiple competitors. The pressure to conform to a stable model, however, produced reactionary misunderstandings of English meter and the culture it stood for. This unstable relationship to poetic form influenced the prose and poems of Robert Graves, Siegfried Sassoon, Wilfred Owen, W. B. Yeats, Ezra Pound, and Alice Meynell. A significant intervention in literary history, this book argues that our contemporary understanding of the rise of modernist poetic form was crucially bound to narratives of English national culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aEnglish languagexVersification. 0aEnglish poetryy19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish poetryy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aNational characteristics, English, in literature. 0aPoeticsxHistoryy19th century. 0aPoeticsxHistoryy20th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh  aArthur Brock.  aCraiglockhart War Hospital.  aEnglish education.  aEnglish language.  aEnglish literature.  aEnglish meter.  aEnglish poet.  aEnglish poetry.  aEnglish prosody.  aEnglish soldiers.  aEzra Pound.  aGeorge Saintsbury.  aGerard Manley Hopkins.  aHenry Newbold.  aMatthew Arnold.  aMilton's Prosody.  aRobert Bridges.  aSociety for Pure English.  aVictorian England.  aVictorian meter.  aVictorian tradition.  aW. H. R. Rivers.  agrammatical history.  aliterary movements.  ametrical communities.  ametrical culture.  ametrical history.  ametrical mastery.  ametrical poetry.  anational identity.  apatri